DISCHARGE STANDARDS AND SEWER USE REQUIREMENTS (§ 21-1501)
    It shall be unlawful to discharge into the wastewater system of the Districtxcept in accordance with this chapter.
    General Prohibitions. A User shall not introduce into the District’sastewater system any pollutant which causes pass through or interference. Theseeneral prohibitions and the specific prohibitions in § 1501.4 apply to anyser introducing pollutants
      into the District’s wastewater system whether orot the User is subject to National Pretreatment Standards or National, State,istrict or local pretreatment standards or requirements.
    Affirmative Defenses. A User shall have an affirmative defense in any actionrought against it alleging a violation of the general prohibitions establishedn § 1501.2 and the specific prohibitions in § 1501.4(c)-(g) where the Useran demonstrate that:

      (a)
      It did not know or have reason to know that its discharge, alone or inonjunction with a discharge or discharges from other sources, would cause passhrough or interference; and


      (b)
      One (1) of the following conditions:

    A local limit designed to prevent pass through and/or interference, as the caseay be, was developed in accordance with paragraph 40 C.F.R. § 403.5(c) forach pollutant in the User&#8217;s discharge that caused pass through ornterference, and the
      User was in compliance with each such local limit directlyrior to and during the pass through or interference; or
    If a local limit designed to prevent pass through and/or interference, as thease may be, has not been developed in accordance with 40 C.F.R. § 403.5(c) forhe pollutant(s) that caused the pass through or interference, the User&#8217;sischarge directly
      prior to and during the pass through or interference did nothange substantially in nature or constituents from the User&#8217;s priorischarge activity when WASA was regularly in compliance with WASA&#8217;sational Pollutant Discharge Elimination
      System (NPDES) permit requirements and,n the case of interference, applicable requirements for beneficial reuse ofiosolids.
    Specific Prohibitions: No User shall introduce the following pollutants into theistrict’s wastewater system:

      (a)
      Pollutants which create a fire or explosion hazard in the District&#8217;sastewater system, including, but not limited to:

    Waste streams with a closed-cup flashpoint of less than one hundred fortyegrees Fahrenheit (140° F) or sixty degrees Centigrade (60° C) using testethods specified in 40 C.F.R. Chapter I, Subchapter N, Part 261.21;
    Waste streams causing two (2) readings on an explosion hazard meter at the pointf discharge into the District’s wastewater system, or at any point in theistrict’s wastewater system, of more than five percent (5%) or any singleeading over ten percent
      (10%) of the Lower Explosive Limit of the meter;
    Any liquids, solids, or gases, which by reason of their nature or quantity are,r may be, sufficient either alone or by interaction with other substances toreate fire or explosion or to injure in any other way the wastewater system orhe process or
      operation and maintenance of the wastewater system;
    Gasoline;
    Kerosene;
    Naphtha;
    Ethers;
    Alcohols;
    Ketones;
    Aldehydes;
    Peroxides;
    Chlorates;
    Perchlorates;
    Bromates;
    Carbides;
    Hydrides; and
    Sulfides;

      (b)
      Pollutants which have a pH of less than five (5.0) or more than ten (10.0),xcept when a waiver to the upper pH limit is authorized in writing by WASA, orhich have any corrosive property capable of damaging or creating a hazard totructures, equipment,
        processes, or personnel of the District&#8217;sastewater system, including, but not limited to, acids, sulfides, concentratedhloride and fluoride compounds, and substances which will react with water toorm acidic or alkaline products;


      (c)
      Solid or viscous substances in amounts which may cause, or contribute tobstruction of the flow in a sewer or otherwise interfere with the operation ofhe District’s wastewater system, including, but not limited to:

    Substances which may solidify or become viscous at temperatures above thirty-twoegrees Fahrenheit (32° F) or zero degrees Centigrade (0° C);
    Solids having any linear dimensions greater than one inch (1 in.);
    Fats, oils, and grease;
    Incompletely shredded garbage;
    Animal remains;
    Blood;
    Feathers;
    Ashes;
    Cinders;
    Sand;
    Spent lime;
    Stone or marble dust;
    Metal;
    Glass;
