      Unless WASA specifically authorizes any substance including, but not limitedo:

    Septic tank sludge;
    Restaurant grease;
    Waste from a fuel service station;
    Waste from a marine holding tank; and
    Waste from a portable toilet;

      (l)
      Sludges, screenings, or other residues from the pretreatment of industrialastes;


      (m)
      Medical or infectious wastes except as WASA specifically authorizes inriting;


      (n)
      Wastewater causing, alone or in conjunction with other sources, the effluentrom Blue Plains to fail toxicity tests;


      (o)
      Detergents, surface-active agents, or other substances which might causexcessive foaming in the District’s wastewater system;

    Any waste that if otherwise disposed of would be a hazardous waste, unlesspecifically authorized in writing by WASA; or
    Any substance which, alone or in conjunction with a discharge or discharges fromther sources, causes or may cause, or contributes to, a violation of anyequirement of the Blue Plains Title V permit issued pursuant to the Clean Airct.
    Pharmaceutical waste shall not be discharged to the District’s wastewaterystem if they contain materials in amounts that will contribute to or result inastewater concentrations that cause or contribute to pass through ornterference.
    Health care facilities located in the District of Columbia shall not dischargeharmaceutical products or pharmaceutical wastes into the District’sastewater system except in accordance with District laws and regulations.
    Excreta from individuals undergoing medical diagnosis or therapy withadioactive material shall be exempt from any limitations contained in thishapter.
